  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 9.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The threshingfloor of Chidon",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". For Chidon, the parallel place has ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Nachon",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; possibly these are two names of the same place, or one form is a corruption of the ether; but there is nothing to determine for us which. Owing to the meaning of Nachon being \"prepared,\" the version of Aquila is \"to the prepared threshingfloor,\" with which the Jonathan Targum agrees, and (for this Chronicles passage) the Joseph Targum gives ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "אֲתַר מְתַקַּן",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "threshing-",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "floor was a circular plot of hard ground, from fifty to one hundred feet in diameter, on which the oxen trampled out the grain. Threshingfloors evidently often became landmarks, and helped to designate places (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 50:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 24:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The oxen stumbled",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In the parallel place the Authorized Version renders \"shook it.\" The Hebrew verb is the same (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "שָׁמַט",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") in both places. Its elementary meanings are \"to strike\" and \"to throw down.\" Perhaps the meaning is near the Vulgate rendering, c",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "alcitrabant",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and equivalent to the rendering, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "became restive.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " 1 Chronicles 13:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "As the whole assembly approved of David's design (כּן לעשׂות, it is to do so  equals  so much we do), David collected the whole of Israel to carry it out. \"The whole of Israel,\" from the southern frontier of Canaan to the northern; but of course all are not said to have been present, but there were numerous representatives from every part, - according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 6:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", a chosen number of 30,000 men. The מצרים שׁיחור, which is named as the southern frontier, is not the Nile, although it also is called שׁחר (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 23:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 2:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and the name \"the black river\" also suits it (see Del. on Isaiah, loc. cit.); but is the שׁיחור before, i.e., eastward from Egypt (מצרים על־פּני אשׁר), i.e., the brook of Egypt, מצרים נחל, the Rhinocorura, now el Arish, which in all accurate statements of the frontiers is spoken of as the southern, in contrast to the neighbourhood of Hamath, which was the northern boundary: see on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 34:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". For the designation of the northern frontier, חמת לבוא, see on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 34:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Kirjath-jearim, the Canaanitish Baalah, was known among the Israelites by the name Baale Jehudah or Kirjath-baal, as distinguished from other cities named after Baal, and is now the still considerable village Kureyeh el Enab; see on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 9:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In this fact we find the explanation of י אל ק בּעלתה, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 13:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " : to Baalah, to Kirjath-jearim of Judah. The ark had been brought thither when the Philistines sent it back to Beth-shemesh, and had been set down in the house of Abinadab, where it remained for about seventy years; see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 7:1-2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and the remarks on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 6:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". שׁם נקרא אשׁר is not to be translated \"which is named name,\" which gives no proper sense. Translating it so, Bertheau would alter שׁם into שׁם, according to an arbitrary conjecture of Thenius on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 6:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"who there (by the ark) is invoked.\" But were שׁם the true reading, it could not refer to the ark, but only to the preceding משּׁם, since in the whole Old Testament the idea that by or at the resting-place of the ark Jahve was invoked (which שׁם אשׁר would signify) nowhere occurs, since no one could venture to approach the ark. If שׁם referred to משּׁם, it would signify that Jahve was invoked at Kirjath-baal, that there a place of worship had been erected by the ark; but of that the history says nothing, and it would, moreover, be contrary to the statement that the ark was not visited in the days of Saul. We must consequently reject the proposal to alter שׁם into שׁם as useless and unsuitable, and seek for another explanation: we must take אשׁר in the sense of ὡς, which it sometimes has; cf. Ew. 333, a.: \"as he is called by name,\" where שׁם does not refer only to יהוה, but also to the additional clause הכּרוּבים יושׁב, and the meaning is that Jahve is invoked as He who is enthroned above the cherubim; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 80:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
